## Run it

```sh
cp .env.example .env        # fill in secrets/config (.env is gitignored)
docker compose up -d        # start the stack
docker compose config -q    # validate the compose file
docker compose down         # stop (add -v to also drop named volumes/data)
```

## How a change ships

```mermaid
flowchart LR
    Edit["Edit compose.yaml / a service / config"] --> Val["docker compose config -q"]
    Val -->|valid| Up["docker compose up -d (try locally)"]
    Up --> Commit["Conventional commit + push"]
    Commit --> CI["CI: docker compose config -q"]
```

## What's committed vs not

- **Committed (config):** `compose.yaml`, `.env.example`, any service config files (mount them
  read-only, e.g. `./config/app.conf:/etc/app/app.conf:ro`), and any `Dockerfile`s.
- **Not committed (data):** persistent data uses **named volumes** (Docker-managed, outside the
  repo). If you bind-mount data to a local folder instead, add that folder to `.gitignore`.
- **Secrets:** real values live in `.env` (gitignored); `.env.example` is the committed template.

See [`AGENTS.md`](AGENTS.md) for the START-HERE map. Follows the
[RepoKit](https://github.com/PBNZ/repo-kit) standard.
